{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514383","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514383"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:21:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:21:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12311"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12311","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12311"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.07,0.25,0.42,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4832"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66601"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4832","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4832"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12311"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52054"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"2308"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"2777"},{"type":"tags","id":"2977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7778"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7807"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15241"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21407"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42735"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66601","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66601"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-hour history of severe headache, blurred vision, neck stiffness, nausea, chest pain and palpitations. These symptoms began shortly after dinner, where he consumed chicken liver p\u00e2t\u00e9, smoked fish, and a glass of wine. He has a history of depression, which has been difficult to treat. Over the past few years, his psychiatrist has prescribed various antidepressants, combinations, and augmenting agents. His current medication was started 10 months ago, but he cannot recall its name. He does not take any other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 115/min, blood pressure 205/125 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. He is alert but agitated, making it difficult to obtain a clear history.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of the patient\u0027s symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sertraline","Mirtazapine","Amitriptyline","Phenelzine","Venlafaxine"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s presentation is highly suggestive of a hypertensive crisis caused by a monoamine oxidase inhibitor (MAOI) interaction with tyramine-rich foods. \u003Cstrong\u003EPhenelzine\u003C/strong\u003E is a non-selective and irreversible MAOI primarily used as an antidepressant and anxiolytic. It inhibits the breakdown of monoamines (including serotonin, dopamine, and norepinephrine) in the brain and gut. When a patient taking an MAOI consumes tyramine-rich foods (such as aged cheeses, cured meats, fermented foods, and certain alcoholic beverages), it can lead to a dangerous accumulation of tyramine, resulting in a hypertensive crisis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESertraline\u003C/strong\u003E is a selective serotonin reuptake inhibitor (SSRI). While it can cause side effects such as nausea, insomnia, and headache, it does not interact with tyramine-rich foods and would not cause a hypertensive crisis of this magnitude.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmitriptyline\u003C/strong\u003E is a tricyclic antidepressant that inhibits norepinephrine and serotonin reuptake. Its common side effects include dry mouth, drowsiness, and constipation, but it does not interact with tyramine-rich foods in the way that MAOIs do.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVenlafaxine\u003C/strong\u003E is a serotonin-norepinephrine reuptake inhibitor (SNRI). While it can cause side effects like dizziness, nausea, and increased blood pressure, it does not cause the severe hypertensive crisis seen with MAOI-tyramine interactions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMirtazapine\u003C/strong\u003E is a noradrenergic and specific serotonergic antidepressant (NaSSA). Its side effects can include sedation, increased appetite, and weight gain, but it does not have the potential for dangerous food interactions like MAOIs and therefore cannot cause this patients presentation. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key to diagnosing this case is recognizing the classic presentation of an MAOI-tyramine interaction: sudden onset of severe headache, hypertension, and other autonomic symptoms following the consumption of tyramine-rich foods. This scenario underscores the importance of patient education regarding dietary restrictions when prescribing MAOIs, as well as the need for clinicians to be aware of this potentially life-threatening interaction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Tyramine-containing foods are contraindicated with phenelzine as they can cause hypertensive crisis.","Monoamine oxidase inhibitors (MAOIs) like phenelzine require strict dietary restrictions to prevent potentially life-threatening interactions.","Symptoms of hypertensive crisis include severe headache, blurred vision, neck stiffness, nausea, chest pain, and palpitations."],"references":["Brown C, Taniguchi G, Yip K. The monoamine oxidase inhibitor-tyramine interaction. J Clin Pharmacol. 1989 Jun;29(6):529-32. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/2666453/","Rapaport MH. Dietary restrictions and drug interactions with monoamine oxidase inhibitors: the state of the art. J Clin Psychiatry. 2007;68 Suppl 8:42-6. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17640157/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52054"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12311"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52054","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52054"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-01T14:57:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-01T14:58:58+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4832"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66601"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"43","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/43"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc8a","name":"Pharmacology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"rel